Media notes: A surprise Prairie Warbler was singing at a roadside stop we made near Sadieville, KY, just off Interstate 75. Locality: Kawartha Highlands Signature Site Provincial Park--Long Lake
Observation Details: Singing all morning from branches overhanging cliff face. Song frequency is about 10-12s intervals with occasional pauses. Showing signs of territoriality - seems to be staying in one small area for this entire entire morning. I saw other warblers lurking about but was unable to confirm a pair (CSWA are also here). Location: Long Lake’s first cove on the north side, atop a cliff face at about the opening to that bay. He’s singing from the top of a rock wall. Access by boat only - it’s a pretty easy paddle.

At 9:15 am driving slowly with the windows down along Sugar Bottom Beach Rd there came through the driver’s side that thin buzzy song rising and accelerating that could only be the song of the Prairie Warbler. From 41.7633493, -91.5564956, the song seemed to be coming from a small clump of taller trees, and I eventually followed the rapid strains to a small warbler silhouette singing in the upper outer branches of a honey locust. Backlit, the warbler was dimly patterned, but clearly the source of the song. I moved into a better position, almost directly below the warbler and looked straight up to see all the field markings come into focus: solid yellow from throat to base of long all-white tail, dark neck spots and black tiger stripes on sides, dark semi-circle under eye. Recorded audio and sent alert. In minutes, as I was sitting under the tree of the singing bird, Caswell, Hester, Madsen, and VanDeWalle arrived on the scene and all quickly got eyes and ears on the rare Prairie. Audio.

Media notes: Both male and female Prairie Warblers seen while calling. The male gave the lower call and the female the higher, sharper (alarm) call.
Observation Details: We watched a pair that clearly were agitated by our presence, the female soon seen carrying a small, green caterpillar. The calls were distinctly different, but may have been context related. The male's call was a lower, harder chip, while the female gave a higher, sharper call that was probably her alarm note. It is possible the male gave his typical call note rather than an alarm call. We also heard and watched a male singing on north side of the road.  Postscript: Trevor had detected this bird an another south of here along the cut on 24 June. This species is expanding in the region and using power line cuts that provide the perfect habitat for them. With the pair, we saw them both clearly, often dipping their tails slightly as is typical. Both were bright yellow on the underpart and showed yellowish wing bars (not bold), and greenish upperparts. The male had bold black bars on the face and streaks down sides; his back was olive green with rusty streaks. The bills were black. The female had dusky facial markings in the same pattern as the male. The tail had long and narrow white on the inner webs of the outer tail feathers. The undertail coverts were off white to dull yellow. The singing male sang a high, rising, and slightly accelerating sizzling song.

Media notes: Prairie Warbler twice sings his rising, accelerating song, each time ending with a buzzy note. In the background are Common Yellowthroat, who is proudly proclaiming his Wichita ancestry, and Pine Warbler, who is merrily trilling within his beloved eponymous habitat. There is also some noise, unfortunately, from the usual trifecta of dissonance: wind, walking, and handling.  I captured this audio in .mp4 format by taking a video with my Samsung S5. Using the program Ocenaudio, I extracted the audio in .wav format and created a copy of the sound file. Then I applied minimal edits: only trimming the recording and normalizing the volume to -3 dB.
Observation Details: Lifer!! I entered Pine Tree Trail from the west side (lakeside) trailhead. Only a few steps in, I realized I was hearing a vaguely familiar bird song (something I've studied, but haven't experienced in person). So I followed the sound and quickly came to a small sandy clearing. I soon found an overall bright yellow warbler with cheeks outlined in bold black, similarly bold black streaks on its sides that faded down the flanks, dark wings, and an olive crown and nape. I quickly recognized it as an adult male Prairie Warbler! I couldn't see any red on his back, but I read that this is not unusual. I noted that he was pumping his tail. He was singing up a storm! He even sang two versions of the same song: both were rising in pitch, but one was slow and measured, the other was fast and accelerated. I recorded the latter.

Media notes: Adult male Prairie Warbler sings his "Group A" (current or prospective mate) song from center-stage--somewhere in the tall-grass enshrouded & thorn-tangled center of a 2+ acre field adjacent to an abandoned farmhouse.  For a species on the Watch List suffering decline due to habitat loss, an abandoned farm property has huge potential. Fields which formerly were cultivated, managed & maintained for cattle or crops are soon overrun & overgrown. Habitat restoration through neglect; powerful and simple. If only we could keep the property in this state. Alas, I fear it won't last.   At least 3 other male PRWA also heard singing from different patches in/around this field. At least 8 total individuals detected between start and finish.
Observation Details: First time observing PRWA, but I'm confident of at least 8 individuals. Let's run through my tally--  + 2 heard singing in scrubby field bordering St. Michael's at the beginning + 4-6 heard singing in scrubby field behind abandoned farmhouse, the return point of my trek; + 2 seen (briefly but unmistakably) in low shrubs north of the cul-de-sac on my return journey; --> ∑(Minimum) = 2+4+2 = 8.  I imagine the surplus of undisturbed brushy fields bordering open woodlands is the reason for their high concentration here. I've recorded some audio of other species but I'm fairly certain PRWA is in the background of at least a couple of these. Will post audio later if this is helpful.
The audio has an eastern towhee in the foreground. The prairie warbler is more distant.

Media notes: Male on territory at west side of clearing, singing from ~12 meters high in white pine, foraging as well. At least 40 meters from nest.
Observation Details: Male singing above car first thing shortly after dawn broke. Stood near him for some time, watching as he sang and occasionally moved from one perch to another, noting that he seemed to favour one above small open space adjacent to roadside, his attention drawn downward here. Eventually there was movement below, and I looked down to see female on low bough of white pine for a moment before disappearing. Male moved off as well at this time, his songs becoming quiet and infrequent. I wandered down and stood at spot where female appeared, lowering myself and searching edge of bushes at roadside where she must have flown from. To my surprise there was a fresh structure, relatively visible from this angle, tucked in main fork of small deciduous shrub right next to road where it was completely concealed from sight but car tires surely pass within two meters of it. I walked up to it, puzzled, to find it completely empty. I left for a little while, and returned to have a closer look at structure again. To my surprise (somehow) she flushed off of nest at two meters and flew to sit in the open on the same pine bough as earlier, chip quietly, and fly away. Apparently incubation of empty nests has been documented in several non-passerine and passerine species such as Great Tit, Common Blackbird, and Pied Flycatcher - perhaps this is another case of this.   Also spent several hours off at the west side of the clearing with the neighbouring pair. As I walked down the road over to the other side, the male was singing quietly high above me on one of the tower beams. Raising binoculars, I noticed a fat green bug in his bill. His song wasn't just quiet, it was muffled. A few moments later he dropped and flew far, vanishing well beyond peak of hill. I wandered up and around to the other side where I relocated him, foraging and singing occasionally at the peaks of pines at edge of clearing. After an hour or so watching them I found the nest tucked in tiny fork one meter high in the middle of a very bouncy juniper branch, containing two chicks, as well as two unhatched eggs.

Also fighting courtship-type behavior several times between male and female. Also a different female carrying grasses.  And a male carrying what looked to be a moth, but could have been leaves - although I am not sure if males of this species help build the nest - or even what the nest is made of..   Pics.  Audio.  Carefully counting in one direction as to avoid double counting. I actually subtracted two off my final count as a buffer. I am pretty sure I have one nesting tree located which I hope to check on later this summer.

Observation Details: First for Hotspot! Heard singing at 12:15 and again at 12:24 in the Northern Pine Forest. Song was a series of ascending buzzy notes that was about 12-14 notes long. I got up on the small embankment at the south west corner of the Northern Array and got an audio recording. Light pishing brought the bird out right at my feet and I was able to get some pictures. Yellow throat, breast and belly with dark black streaks extending from below the bird's eye through it's flanks. Rusty red patch on mantle seen very clearly. Black eyeline and under eye arc. What an exciting species to have at my favorite hotspot!

Observation Details: Continuing bird first found last night by Annie Aguirre, et al.  Small yellowish warbler with a dark greenish back in flight and with distinctive thick black streaks along the flanks and also with a curved black streak under eye that connected with the black lores. Although in the photos the right side of the bird's face has more yellow in the upward turn of the sub-auricular streak.  A very small bird when seen unaided on a nearby branch, probably a little smaller than the Yellow Warblers.   Seen along the north side of the creek along the Alder Loop trail. From the parking area along 131 south of the Little Elkhart River you cross four bridges, the fourth bridge crosses the north loop of the bifurcated Little Elkhart River, and then continue walking through the excessively muddy trail to where it takes a southward turn and comes close to the river, north of a lot of dead trees on the south side of this stream-which can be seen on the google map- which area is just west of the double culverts to the east.  This is the area where the bird was. It was on the north side of the trail in the shrubs and right along the stream low in the trees, sometimes @ 5-8 feet above ground.  It seemed to be hanging around a couple of Yellow Warblers, which it was smaller than. First really seen when it was in flight along the stream following these two warblers. It alighted in a tree near the trail, then moved to the more shrubby area on the north side of the trail and into the higher tree limbs above.  Strange wetland habitat choice for a "Prairie" Warbler.  Bird was chip calling at first, and had already been found by Duane Lehman when I arrived at this part of the trail. It would also do short abbreviated songs. Later on the way back it seemed to be singing a little longer version of it's song, but not a full song with the long increasing pitch.

Background Species: Catharus guttatus -- Hermit Thrush; Vireo plumbeus -- Plumbeous Vireo; Troglodytes aedon -- House Wren; Dryobates arizonae -- Arizona Woodpecker; Junco phaeonotus -- Yellow-eyed Junco; Piranga flava -- Hepatic Tanager
Media notes: Advertising song of adult male Prairie Warbler, a vagrant here in Rucker Canyon, 1600m. It was singing intermittently while foraging in blooming live oak trees at the edge of the riparian along Rucker Creek about .2 miles below Cypress Campground. Warm (75F) now (9:20AM, 16 May 2019) on a partly cloudy day (60% cloud cover) that started out clear and calm and 49F, but has increasingly become cloudy and breezy. Background of first cut includes Hermit Thrush singing; 2nd cut includes Piranga sp., Plumbeous Vireo, House Wren, Arizona Woodpecker call; 3rd cut includes presumed Yellow-eyed Junco, Plumbeous Vireo, same Piranga (proabably Hepatic), & House Wren.
Observation Details: An intermittently given buzzy song, when I tracked it down, turned out to be a male Prairie Warbler singing as it foraged through blooming live oaks at the edge of the riparian of Arizona sycamores, pines, and Arizona cypress along the road .2 miles below the entrance to Cypress Campground in Rucker Canyon, 1600m, on 16 May 2019. I recorded its song (ML159605231), watching it from 9:15-10:00AM. I then hiked back to the campsite at the end of the road in Rucker Canyon to get Richard Webster, who drove us back down ca. 10:40A. We relocated it by its song--even less frequently given now as it was getting windier and later. I then watched it--and photographed it--while Richard went back to break camp and pick me up. I left the Prairie Warbler about 11:50A, continuing down the road birding for another 15 minutes. A rare spring vagrant in Arizona, and my first for Cochise County.

Another great yard bird. I thought I heard it across the street on the neighbor's property when I left the  house this morning at 6:10am. The setting seemed off, though, so I let it go and went on with my day. When we pulled into the driveway this afternoon, I heard the buzzy, rising call again and kept thinking that had to be what it was. This time, I played the call on my phone just to see if it could indeed be a Prairie Warbler. Sure enough, it flew right into the pine tree next to our driveway and worked its way down into the bush below it.

I am running out of adjectives to describe the fine beauty of all the birds we saw today. Over the course of our paddle, 4 male Prairie Warblers responded enthusiastically to pishing in four different places. They were in full spectacular plumage, with the clear black marks near their faces and olive backs and shining lemon underbellies. Several were so close I could have reached my hand out and touched them. One sang.

Details submitted to MOURC:  On 7 June 2015, Drew Smith, Susan Fall and I arrived at Hastings Sand Coulee S.N.A. at 7:00 a.m. to search for the Bewick’s Wren first reported on 1 June by Tom Lewanski. About 10:00 a.m. I was surprised to hear the distinctive song of a Prairie Warbler and alerted Drew and Susan. Soon we were able to see it as it continued singing several songs per minute until 10:35 a.m. (some 75-100 songs total). We were joined at 10:20 by Tom and Alex Lewanski; both heard it well and Alex got good views also. We are confident that this bird did not sing from this location prior to 10:00 since from our separate monitoring positions we were very unlikely to have overlooked it. At 10:35 it quit singing and flew to the north. Tom and Alex spent the rest of the morning searching in the direction it flew but were unable to relocate it. I made subsequent trips to that area on 9 June (6:45-10:05 a.m.) and 19 June (6:35-09:20 a.m.) and did not record it. We presume this was a wandering vagrant male attempting to solicit a mate by singing in a temporary territory, then moving on. We verbally described field marks while we watched it; when I returned home I wrote the description on my computer before I consulted references. I recorded six songs, three consecutive ones and then 20 min. later, three more (Marantz PMD-660 digital recorder, Sennheiser ME-67 directional microphone). The songs were very distinctive: a series of about 15 evenly spaced sharp buzzy notes, the first few on the same pitch, then remainder rising steadily in pitch, zee-zee-zee-zee- . . . -zee-zee-zee, with a buzzy but piercing quality similar to “zee” notes of Black-throated Green Warbler “zee-zee-zee-zoo-zee” song. Drew, Susan, and I had good views from as close as about 20m. It was a small warbler appearing a bit smaller and more slender than Yellow Warbler (but none present for direct comparison); yellow below, pale undertail coverts, dark streaks on sides, olive above. Face pattern unique: black arc below eye from bill gape to cheek; yellow above that but below eye; black through eye; yellow supercilium; crown olive. Back did not have bold rufous streaks but we saw a hint of rufous, possibly suggesting 2nd-year male. Wing bars weak but present. We did not observe tail bobbing, or white in tail. [Dunn and Garrett note that males do not normally bob their tails when singing from a song perch.] Sang from scrubby oak saplings mostly but also in more mature oaks. The habitat (scattered oak saplings, sumac stands) looked quite suitable for this species. Below is the first recording of three consecutive songs (starting at 10:02 a.m.), unedited except for high pass filter (1500 Hz) to reduce low-frequency background noise. This was typical of the spacing of songs over the 35 min. we heard and watched it.

Unusual for the location. Singing in the same spot where I had a PRAW (presumably the same bird) two weeks ago. It would be interesting to see if it stays the summer there although breeding seems unlikely if only because I have only seen the single bird.

Found around the tuttle drive entrance. I was checking a bee research block when I heard what I thought was a some type of warbler. Upon further investigation, I spotted a warbler with a bright yellow throat, breast, and belly. I then heard the song and was able to resolve that it was a prairie warbler. There was a PRAW found hear last june so this is not unheard of at this location. My original intent for this visit was not necessarily birding but I first heard what appeared to be a Prairie Warbler. I continued on to do the task that I had originally came to do. After I was done, I got my recording equipment out in the case that I heard this again. I walked to the location that I had originally heard it and waited for about an hour. I walked around for another hour and a half and finally heard the tell tale pitch of this warbler. I managed to attain a recording of it and afforded a few good looks. For those that may go to look for this, please respect this fragile ecosystem. Please do not cause any erosion on the slopes. Respect the land being that it is a Scientific and Natural Area. Please leave plants, animals, rocks, and other natural elements in place to fulfill their life cycle and role in the environment.   Field notes: - Bold black streaks on sides and flanks - Bright yellow eyebrow strip - Dark line through eye
